				<td colspan="2"><span>Pem, 
<br />
  A few things that might help. 
<br />

<br />
   Buy some sow potions. I know it's money and a pain in the a$ but trust me, if you have those going then you don't have to worry about twisting in speed song, it really helps to be able to concentrate on the swarm instead of worrying about keeping your speed up, especially when you're learning. 
<br />
   A few things a bard friend told me when I first started swarming that made a big difference: (this may not always apply but they are good general rules, I don't claim to know everything I just hope this helps). 
<br />

<br />
    You always want to try and swarm mobs that have the same run speed. It's also important to get mobs that assist each other, or have social aggro. A good example of a place to practice if you're looking for a safe spot is the Aviak village in South Karana. 
<br />
Set your spells up like this: 
<br />

<br />
(assuming you are using sow potions)
<br />

<br />
1. DoT
<br />
2. DoT
<br />
3. Snare
<br />
4. Charm
<br />
5. invis
<br />

<br />
Always use single target songs NEVER use AE dots or snares, swarming will not work if you do. This is very important. Also, a trick that really helps, go into your keyboard setup in options and asign a key to the &quot;target toggle&quot; I think it's called. This will make it so that you cam switch between the last 2 targets with one button, making swarming a whole lot easier. 
<br />
Now to start. I'll do a quick run through at the Aviak village in South Karana since it's an easy place to practice this, all greens. 
<br />
   Run up to the top of the treehouse, once at the top fire up a fresh sow and pick a target (anyone but the vendor up there). Generally it's a good idea to swarm strongest to weakest, so if there's an Aviak Avocet up there, target him. Throw on your dot song and when it lands start runing down the ramp, by the time you hit the bottom you should have 5 or 6 of the little buggars behind you. Don't worry they're all green, just keep your distance and try and run around them, packing them into a single group. Keep the original one you Dot'd Targetted!! Now you should have them bunched in together still running after you with the original target unchanged, right? Charm the one you have targetted (the one you pulled with a dot). Now pick another one and sick your new pet on it, because the one you charmed is the only one with more than just social aggro, they should jump on your pet. If you get one or two stragglers (which happens) try to run the stragglers through your pet but DON'T cast on them! 
<br />
Now you should have a group of mobs in front of you beating on your pet, when the pet gets down to about 15-20% break the charm by using your invis song and then dot your old pet to death to take the xp. Target the last one you had your pet attack, charm away and keep going. 
<br />
   It seems complicated but it's really not once you get it, kind of like riding a bike  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />
<br />
The most important thing is aggro management, that's what swarming is really all about. Remember that in order to keep the swarm on your pet you cannot piss ANY of the other mobs off, you want all of them to be coming after you just because you hit thier friend, that's it. Because that's the case, they will assist when you sick your pet on one of them, instead of just coming after you. As soon as you hit one of them or land a song on one of them, that one will have more than social aggro and probably will not assist the others in killing your pet because he's more interested in you. 
<br />

<br />
Hope that helps man, give it a shot in South Karana first, even the spires in SK are good because the gnolls there assist each other. After that you can do swarming in all kinds of great places like Jaggedpine and Ocean of Tears. 
<br />
You'll see just don't give up!
<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
